{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"abf945fd-49a8-4537-9772-c77d9d78b596","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Find your process:**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**3. Collect a trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\n**4. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**5. Analyze** — open in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [speedscope.app](https://speedscope.app) (use `--format speedscope` during collect for the latter).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools (distroless image), use **`dotnet-trace`** via a sidecar or [diagnostic port forwarding](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/diagnostics/dotnet-trace#collect-using-diagnostic-port).\n- For production-safe, low-overhead sampling, `cpu-sampling` is the right profile — it uses EventPipe, not a profiler attach.\n- Add `--buffersize 256` if you're seeing dropped events under heavy load.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bc3b58fa-32bc-4f3d-af95-da2fb88ab421","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a diagnostic/troubleshooting question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise, practical advice.","outputTokens":430,"requestId":"6000:1CA5E9:28A3B9:302F35:69EAC5FB"},"id":"c759cdc0-5d97-484a-8792-1bb1f8442e7a","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:23:17.765Z","parentId":"530a85da-6c92-4c88-a8ff-befa7eef3ea2"}
